Exhibition That Provoked Unforeseen Consequences -- tOther Tongues: Language and Hybridity in Recent Canadian Video Art -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis forum of current discussions of ethics and aesthetics addresses a cross-section of disciplines including literary theory, philosophy, women's studies, postcolonial theory, art history, Holocaust studies, theology, and others. Contributors, ranging from philosophers and literary critics to practicing artists and art curators, answer such questions as: In the age of the collapse of metaphysics, what is the relation between philosophical reflection and art? If we question the privilege accorded to the aesthetic, can ethics alone offer a solution to the crisis of representation? Is it possible and ethically viable to represent the other in speech and image? What happens at the conjunction of aesthetics and politics? Can one speak of aesthetic configurations of the space of community? Are the concepts of ethics and aesthetics gendered and repressive of sexual difference? Considering the many works that consider either ethics or aesthetics almost exclusively within the confines of particular disciplines, this collection crosses the boundaries and continues the debate outside the rigid parameters of specialized discourses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAesthetics. 0aArtxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aEthics. 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aBociurkiw, Marusya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoos, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoos, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChanter, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https:/